pvalue = 1-pt(2.485, df=25)

alternately,

pvalue = pt(2.485, df=25, lower.tail=FALSE)
pvalue
## [1] 0.0100024

Since p less than alpha \(p > \alpha\), we will will fail to reject the null hypothesis at \(\alpha = 0.01\).

5.12

  1. Let \(\mu\) be the population average lead concentration (in \(\mu\)g/l) of police officers subjected to inhalation of automobile exhaust fumes.

Our hypotheses are \[ H_0: \mu = 35, \, \, H_A: \mu > 35 \]

  1. Assumptions:
    • police officers are sampled independently of each other
    • Sample size \(n = 52\) is large enough to assume that the sample mean is approximately normal (by Central Limit Theorem)
  2. Test statistic = \(\frac{124.32-35}{37.74/\sqrt{52}}\). Under null, it follows a t distribution with \(n-1 = 51\) degrees of freedom.

p-value = \(P(T > obs)\)

n = 52; xbar = 124.32; mu0 = 35; s = 37.74
teststat = (xbar-mu0)/(s/sqrt(n))
pvalue = pt(teststat, df=n-1, lower.tail=FALSE)
pvalue # p-value using t-test
## [1] 4.956975e-23
pvalue_z = pnorm(teststat, lower.tail=FALSE)
pvalue_z # p-value using z-test
## [1] 1.314098e-65

Since p-value is less than \(1\%\), we reject \(H_0\) at \(1\%\) level of significance.

In other words, at \(1\%\) level of significance, we have enough evidence to believe that downtown police officers have higher lead exposure than the group in the previous study.

  1. The p-value for a two-sided test \(H_0: \mu = 35, \, \, H_A: \mu \neq 35\) based on this data will be less than \(.01\)
2*pvalue
## [1] 9.913949e-23

and we will reject \(H_0\) in favor of \(H_A\).

So, by duality of 99% confidence interval and a two-sided hypothesis test at 1% level of significance, we can say that the \(99\%\) confidence interval for the average blood concentration level of police officers based on this data will not contain the null value \(35\mu\)g/l.

One population proportion

6.12

  1. sample statistic, since the 1259 selected residents form only a subset of the entire population of US residents.

  2. sample statistic \(\hat{p} = 0.48\),

standard error \(SE(\hat{p}) = \sqrt{\frac{\hat{p}(1-\hat{p})}{n}}\),

\(\alpha = 5\%\), so multiplier = \(z_{\alpha/2} \approx 1.96\),

95% confidence interval: \((\hat{p} - 1.96 \times SE(\hat{p}), \hat{p} + 1.96 \times SE(\hat{p}))\). In R, we use a slightly more accurate value of the multiplier:

alpha = 0.05; n = 1259; phat = 0.48; se = sqrt(phat*(1-phat)/n)
z = -qnorm(alpha/2)
z
## [1] 1.959964
lower = phat - z*se
upper = phat+z*se

lower
## [1] 0.4524033
upper
## [1] 0.5075967

  1. Yes, since \(n \hat{p} = 1259 \times 0.48\) and \(n (1-\hat{p}) = 1259 \times 0.52\) are both larger than \(10\), we can assume that the normal model for \(\hat{p}\) is a good approximation.

  2. No, since the 95% confidence interval contains the value \(0.5\), a test of \(H_0: p = 0.5\) vs. \(H_A: p \neq 0.5\) at \(5\%\) level of significance will fail to reject \(H_0\). So the conclusion of the newspaper is not justified.

6.16

  1. Let \(p\) denote the population proportion of all Americans who decide not to go to college because they cannot afford it.

Our null and alternative hypotheses are:

\(H_0: p = 0.5\) vs. \(H_A: p < 0.5\). (research question in alternative hypothesis)

sample statistic \(\hat{p} = 0.48\), sample size \(n = 331\)

test statistic \(z = \frac{\hat{p}-0.5}{\sqrt{0.5*(1-0.5)/n}}\). Under null, the test statistic follows an approximate N(0,1) distribution.

pvalue = \(P(Z < obs)\)

phat = 0.48; n = 331; p0 = 0.5
teststat = (0.48-0.5)/(sqrt(0.5*(1-0.5)/n))
teststat
## [1] -0.7277362
pvalue = pnorm(teststat)
pvalue
## [1] 0.2333875

Since pvalue is larger than \(0.01\), we fail to reject null at \(1\%\) level of significance.

In other words, at \(1\%\) level of significance, we do not have sufficient evidence that a minority of Americans who decide not to go to college do so because they cannot afford it.

  1. Yes.
